Hey, do you know PAL? Of course you know it as a color encoding system for analogue Television. But in this post I&#8217;ll introduce PAL from codeplex.

<a href="https://pal.codeplex.com/" target="_blank">PAL (Performance Analysis of Logs)</a> is an open source tool written by Clint Huffman (MSFT) published on Codeplex to analyze Perfmon log data and Display it in a human readable form.

Ok, you say.  _&#8220;Not just another another performance analysis tool please&#8221;_ &#8230; but..

During my Hyper-V / SCVMM Projects customers have asked me a lot, how they would be able to identify potential performance issues or debug such on their Hyper-V hosts.
  
Or let&#8217;s pick another one. &#8220;I feel my Hyper-V Hosts being in Performance Trouble&#8221; &#8211;> wait.. you feel? :-), ok let&#8217;s proof this feeling&#8230;.
  
My usual answer would be &#8220;use SCOM&#8221;. So Where does PAL fit into the puzzle?

**PAL provides the following functionality
  
** 

  * Analysis of Perfmon Log binaries
  * Aggregate, compare and measure the raw results against predefined threshold definitions
  * Generate human readable reports in HTML Format

## **Requirements**

PAL can be installed on any Workstation or Server and requires .NET 3.5. As the Analysis can take some minutes to hours, depending on how much data you&#8217;ve gathered with perfmon, I&#8217;d suggest not to use a production workload to run the Analysis. PAL consists basically of **two components**.

  * **PAL.ps1** (a powershell script which does the whole analysis Magic)
  * **PalWizard.exe** (a GUI tool to configure the run Options for the Powershell script)

To generate the Graphs in the HTML Report the tool requires <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=14422" target="_blank">.NET 3.5 Chart Controls </a>to be installed.

&nbsp;

## **Usage Example**

Open PAL Wizard

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="502" height="384" />

Change to Threshold File and choose Hyper-V 2012. You may also edit the file to match your experiences, but the defaults are ok so far.

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="513" height="411" />

Export the file to a local path

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="516" height="288" />

Now, open Performance Monitor and connect to your Hyper-V Host

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="633" height="284" />

&nbsp;

Add a new User defined data set using the exported Template

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="637" height="259" />

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="371" height="286" />

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="374" height="290" />

Start collecting performance data (eg. 30 min or an 1h to minimize peak congestions)

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="489" height="210" />

Stop the data collection and copy the raw performance data file to your analysis machine. The file self is saved by default under: %SYSTEMDRIVE%\PerfLogs

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="701" height="301" />

&nbsp;

Go back to PAL Wizard and define the raw data file to analyze

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="497" height="399" />

Fill in the answers corresponding to your Hardware where the performance data came from

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="502" height="402" />

For now we leave all the other options default and press execute to analyze the current data

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="506" height="406" />

&nbsp;

Data is being analyzed and processes. Depending on the amount of data you collected this process can take some minutes or hours to complete.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The tool can be easily automated to analyze more than one data set serial or parallel.

After a while you&#8217;ll get a huge HTML report with tons of useful information grouped by topics that make sense.

&nbsp;

## **Some more words**

As a long term solution I still prefer System Center Operations Manager, however this tool provides real value for ad-hoc analysis with a fair amount of predefined thresholds, so even people not familiar with the performance counters can get a short wrap up about the health and performance state of their Hyper-V Hosts.

I hope I could show how easily it can be to get knowledge on what your Hyper-V Hosts are doing without being a MCPMU (Microsoft certified performance monitor user)
